metadata.name: FXHASH Generative Logo #797
metadata.description:
Unique iteration of the first Generative Token minted on fxhash.

It also servers as the actual logo of the platform. It represents the generative processes driving fxhash tokens. Generative Tokens are fed with a unique hash to produce unique outputs based on the hash — they are functions with a hash as single input.

The growth that comes out of the text is driven by a "Dividing-Aggregating Walkers" (DAW) algorithm. The hash drives all the DAW settings, as well as a mutation factor which is responsible for changes in each Walker parameters as they divide.

Some iterations will produce very simple outputs whereas others might be more chaotic.

Piece by @ciphrd for fxhash

metadata.name: Quantum Plankton #16
metadata.description:
Welcome to the first quantum-computer generated series on fx(hash)!

Quantum Plankton is our generative genesis, the sea where art and science meet and a new sense of aesthetics arises. A collection of shapes and colours, all drawn using the measurement outcomes from quantum computers.

Quantum plankton is composed of 8 palettes and 81 shapes, one of which is always guaranteed to be a pointillistic element.

But how was this done? Take the choice of colours. To choose one of the 8 palettes, we take 3 qubits and entangle them. After, we proceed to measure them, collapsing their wavefunction into three mere binary values. Just about what you need to encode the real numbers up to 8. Hence our little 3 qubits quantum algorithm decides which palette to use.

Using similar processes, all the 81 shapes, including our signature the "pointillism", are drawn onto the canvas.

That is, the underlying rarity of each element in Quantum Plankton has been entirely decided by the laws of quantum mechanics.

metadata.name: Here, After #58
metadata.description:
We were all there
when the sky cried confetti
and if we weren’t, we felt like we had
but here, after
held with each other’s eyes
not much is said at all

——

A : Animate rendering
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Colorleaves #144
metadata.description:
[Pigments are accumulated in the leaves, giving them various shades. Some of the most beautiful foliage features color gradients changing as the season progresses. On some occasions, we ran out of toner.]

metadata.name: Orchard #274
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.
